column1: How many media outlets will be on the Russian Ministry of Justice's list of media designated as foreign agents on 1 June 2019?
column5: ['Less than 3', '3 to 7, inclusive', '8 to 10, inclusive ', '11 to 20, inclusive ', 'More than 20']
column6: ['Non-US Politics']
column11: The list of media outlets designated as foreign agents can be found here. In November 2017, Russia passed a law which allows the government to designate media outlets receiving funding from abroad as "foreign agents" and subject designated entities to additional requirements or sanctions (Reuters). The following month, nine entities were designated as foreign agents, including Voice of America and Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty (Reuters). The designation of individual journalists as foreign agents will not count (e.g., Radio Free Europe). Confused? Check our FAQ or ask us for help.

column6: Update due to no development.
Just a matter of hours left and no change in the list. It is beyond statistically improbable that the list, after not changing for over 2 years will change now.

The list has not been updated since 12th May 2017. The only push for Russian Ministry of Justice to list more media outlets is if the US puts sanctions on Russian media outlets. A question I have been struggling to find an answer is how many other US-funded media outlets are operating in Russia except the already listed as foreign agents? And how many foreign media outlets in numbers and percentages in contrast to domestic media outlets operate in Russia? What I could find out is that the press and internet media is the only possibility for foreign-funded media to use at the moment, as according to multiple sources and especially the report made from Harvard, 94% in shares in television is hold by the state; ( https://scholar.harvard.edu/files/shleifer/files/media.pdf ) while the main read newspapers are actually Russian such as Metro,Moskovsky Komsomolets, Rossiyskaya Gazeta. (https://www.indexoncensorship.org/2013/12/brief-history-russian-media/) and same goes for radio as well - the most listened are Russian owned radios. Another factor to consider is the relations between Russia and the US at the moment and are there any possibilities of Russia listing more media outlets. Such forecast is very volatile as the US-Russia relations are very fragile, however, following the meeting between the U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo and Russian Foreign Minister Sergey Lavrov - both sides are working to collaborate and optimize their relationship. ( https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/apr/11/russia-passes-bill-internet-cut-off-foreign-servers) Points of conflict exist and they are multiple: Syria, the Arctic, Iran, Chinese market, Huawei, Crimea, North Korea and Venezuela among the most reactive and important, as well as the Mueller's investigation which goes along with other European-based investigation on Russian meddling in elections - keeping in mind the European election that is upcoming, this would be a soft belly between Western powers and Russia. Nevertheless, "Moscow may review the decision if Washington halts the crackdown on Russian media, according to the official.
Still no change in the list, highly unlikely another 2 media outlets will be added in the next 2 weeks
Update: There has been no updates to the list since question was posted, I deem it highly unlikely that any changes will be made to the list within the next 2 weeks. Hence, I adjust my probabilities.

Being so close to the end date of the question, which reduces the likelihood that one of the media outlets shuts down, and without significant changes in US-Russian relations on any matter, I put a very high likelihood on the status quo scenario. A possible scenario could be an increase as a result of more Russian media outlets being designated by the EU in the EP election. I do not place a high probability on this scenario, but I still leave a small chance.

I believe, that the number of designated media outlets will remain the same on June 1 of 2019 as it is today, since I assume that the designation was a direct answer from the Russian government to the US actions and media outlets can now prevent being designated knowing the criteria that Russian authorities have established for them.
Russia's list will increase but it will be resistant to increase too much
Forecast Update #3:
Update: Getting closer and no news. (no bankruptcies or adding to the list)
No one has been added since 2017 and we only have a little more than a month to go. Based on that I am going all in on 8 to 10.

The passing of this law seems to be in order to combat the United States' media influence in the region and to crack down on dissenting opinion from their major foreign adversary. After the Mueller report, which explicitly confirms Russian meddling in our democratic elections and paints them in a rather negative and corrupt light, the chance that more media outlets will be designated as foreign agents will increase. There has not been an addition to the list since 2017 and 9 are on the list, but since the Mueller report was a massive document condemning Russia's interference, it's likely that more will be added. However, more than 20 seems unlikely since in two years since the law's passing there has only been outlets added.
Forecast update #2: No news
Currently there are 9, but … some of these may close or merge; or some more may be added (eg, by widening the definition of "media organisation", or by including individuals).

It is most likely that Russia will put between eight and ten media outlets on its Ministry of Justice's list of media designated as foreign agents. Currently, Russia has nine media outlets named on the list, and these nine are the same ones added on December 5th, 2017. Since then, none have gone on as additional outlets, and because of that, it's doubtful that more will be added anytime soon.

As of now, no new media outlets have been added to the list since the original 9 were added on December 5th 2017. Also, because these media outlets were added in under a month after the passage of the law, it makes me suspect that the Russian government had been monitoring media outlet's funding and already knew which ones were "foreign agents". Therefore, I suspect the reason more haven't been added is because there aren't any more that were present before 2017. It also suggests that this once more of a one time law that was meant to send a message, but since then has been forgotten about and lawmakers have failed to enforce it since.
Only two more have to be added to reach 11.
Update 12/04/2019: the list is showing still 9 media. No changes have occurred after November 2017, so I see even less likely the probability of even 2 new outlets in the last month and a half.

Update: 11/04/19 - The list is still showing 9 media. Since June is approaching and changes have not been made to the list after November 2017, it becomes even more likely that the list will remain with 9 media designated as foreign agents.
Rt will be the only state sanctioned news approved for citizens

Seeing as no additions have been added to the list since its creation it is somewhat unlikely that new media outlets will be added in the next two and a half months. I have therefore chosen to give a higher percentage to 8 to 10, inclusive. With that being said I do believe that there is a slight chance, 25 percent to be precise, that some media outlets can be added to the list. I have not given any percentage to any of the reduction options, as I find it unlikely that the Russian government will reduce the list, seeing as the relationship between Russia and the West has not improved since the creation of the list. Another aspect I have taken into account is the fact that Russia in July 2018 passed a law that makes it possible for them to label individual journalists as foreign agents (source: https://europeanjournalists.org/blog/2018/07/05/russia-passes-new-law-to-label-individual-journalists-as-foreign-agents/). This law also gives the government the right to block websites and blogs without a court ruling. The law signals that Russia has not improved its relationship with foreign media, which again strengthens the argument that they will not reduce the list.

16 months ago, the ‘Register of Foreign Media performing the Functions of a Foreign Agent’ came into force. Its establishment was seen as a direct response to the US after the US requested Russia Today, a state-funded Russian media outlet, to register itself as foreign agent pursuant to the ‘Foreign Agent Registration Act’. The register and the new focus on media outlets by Russian regulators might have been a novelty in this form, however, the underlying legal structure mirrors laws which aimed at NGOs by requesting them to register as “foreign agents” (2012 version) and later on allowed the Russian authorities “to prosecute foreign non-governmental organisations (NGOs) or firms designated as ‘undesirable’” (BBC 2015). Since then, the number and the targeted entities remained the same (9 media outlets). Meanwhile, the number of targeted NGOs declined from 135 entities in 2016 to 74 in 2018 as external funding stopped or Russian branches of Western NGOs closed (researched by user @mbayer123). In what extent this decrease has an effect on the assessed probability will be elaborated in the following paragraphs. Furthermore, it is important to consider the remaining time of less than 2 months for the forecast due to its minimizing effect on the probability of an extreme change in the trend. As a logical result, the options which ‘border’ the most likely outcome seem to be more likely than the extremes at the edges.

As base-rate for the forecast at hand serves the history of the Russian foreign agent law, introduced in July 2012. In its original form, it concerned only non-governmental organizations with foreign funding and political activities. In November 2017, it was extended to media outlets. For an adequate estimation of the number of registered media outlets on June 1, 2019, the forecast at hand will consider three things: first, the reasons for the establishment of the law and its extension respectively, the numbers of registered organizations on the list, as well as the reasoning for corresponding labeling and finally, the differences between NGOs and media-outlets will be reviewed. The introduction of the law, in the first place, had primarily domestic reasons, namely the mass protests between the parliamentary and presidential elections in winter 2011/spring 2012 (https://www.dw.com/de/was-ausl%C3%A4ndischer-agent-in-den-usa-und-russland-bedeutet/a-41469379). However, already in 2012, official statements referred to the US Foreign Agent Registration Act (FARA) that itself registers foreign lead organizations and demands disclosure of their finances and activities in the US (https://www.dw.com/de/ngos-in-russland-angeschlagen-aber-ungeschlagen/a-41454896). The amendment of the law and its corresponding extension on media outlets in 2017 were then in fact a direct consequence of the worsening relations between the US and Russia. Washington accused Moscow of having influenced its presidential election in 2016 - also with the help of the state-controlled and financed media outlet RT. As a consequence, RT had to register as a "foreign agent" under FARA on November 13 following a request by US authorities. The Kremlin regarded this as an attack on Russian media and interests and introduced the media law only days after the incident. Today, April 6, 2019 there are 74 organizations registered as foreign agents in Russia (http://unro.minjust.ru/NKOForeignAgent.aspx), as well as 9 media outlets (https://minjust.ru/ru/deyatelnost-v-sfere-nekommercheskih-organizaciy/reestr-inostrannyh-sredstv-massovoy-informacii). While the media outlet list has not changed since December 2017, when exclusively US affiliated media outlets were labeled as foreign agents, only days after the introduction of the law, the corresponding NGO list has faced more changes. While the law was introduced in July 2012, it was not before June 2013 that the first organizations were correspondingly labeled, so round about a year later (http://unro.minjust.ru/NKOForeignAgent.aspx), after preceding public searching of NGO offices in spring 2013. Throughout the years the number of foreign agent changed since many of the affected organizations stopped foreign funding or were dissolved. In July 2016, for instance, there were still 135 organizations on the list (https://www.boell.de/de/2016/09/13/zivilgesellschaft-russland-wo-unterstuetzung-von-aussen-lebensnotwendig-wird), in November 2017 87 (https://www.dw.com/de/ngos-in-russland-angeschlagen-aber-ungeschlagen/a-41454896), and as of today, as above mentioned, 74.

With the Barr Report saying Mueller found election interference from Russia, I see a good chance the number of media outlets designated as foreign agents will increase, and possibly dramatically.

8-10, inclusive - 95%. My prognosis is that the list will stay the same. Since the December 2017, when Russia has declared nine US media outlets to be foreign agents there were no changes in that list. From a personal point of you, it seems to be a one-time thing for Moscow to respond to American sanctions towards Russia. What is more, the question is by June 2019. Considering a very short time period, it is very unlikely that there will be any changes in International Relations that could have an effect on the list. Especially, knowing that on March 5, 2019, Trump already extended U.S. sanctions against Russia for one more year. Hence, Russia had time to respond to it. 11-20, inclusive - 5%. Despite the arguments expressed before, knowing the uncertainties when it comes to politics, in this case, especially, to Russia, I give a very small chance that lists my extended with some extra names.

Considering that “Ministry of Justice's list of media designated as foreign agents” has 9 members which were all uploaded in the same day (05.12.2017) more than 16 months have passed since that day, it is highly likely that such number will remain the same from here to June 1. Furthermore, more than a technical measure based on facts it looks like a political response to US measures adopted in relations to the allegations that Russia interfered in last U. S.’s presidential election (accuses of a mass campaign of disinformation etc). Therefore, I assess an 80% chance that on 1 June 2019 such members of the list will be between “8 to 10, inclusive”.
Increasing probability of status quo due to passage of time.

This measure, implemented around 16 month ago, looks today as a one-time-provision in response to an alleged increasing pressure on Russian media outlets in the United States. Since November 2017, the list - counting 9 members - has not been further modified. There is no reason to believe that the measure will be withdrawn or limited from here to next June, but I assign a slight chance to a scenario where the ongoing investigation on the relations between Trump and Moscow exacerbates the situation.

To me, the law approved by Russia about allowing authorities to list foreign media outlets as “foreign agents” seems an answer to the measure taken by the US after the allegations that Russia interfered in last year’s U.S. presidential election in favour of Trump. “U.S. intelligence officials have accused the Kremlin of using Russian media organizations it finances to influence U.S. voters, and Washington has since required Russian state broadcaster RT to register a U.S.-based affiliate company as a “foreign agent”” https://www.reuters.com/article/us-russia-usa-media-restrictions/russias-putin-signs-foreign-agents-media-law-idUSKBN1DP0I2 It looks like a targeted Russian response to US. That’s why is unlikely that the number of foreign agents would decrease. Additionally, in 2017 the number of media outlets designated as foreign agents was 9 and it has not increased so far, even if there were the conditions for Russia to do that. https://www.bbc.com/news/world-europe-42234582 Concerning the EU, in 2015 has been established a task force to fight cyber disinformation episodes, in particular the ones from Russia. This team has succeeded, and the EU has also warned against possible Russian inference during the campaigns for European elections. Currently, the Commission is even strengthening its battle against the circulation of fake news. It allocated several millions of euros (from 1.9 million euros in 2018 to 5 million euros in 2019 to EEAS, responsible of identifying misinformation campaigns), to this struggle, in particular on internet platforms. https://www.thenewfederalist.eu/european-elections-russia-and-fake-news-under-commission-s-scrutiny In particular, countries like France are fighting a war against disinformation (with the new law to remove "fake news" during electoral campaign and with Macron's claims on Russia medias). This actions could make Russia want to respond, adding new media outlets in its list.

The current list designates 9 medias as foreign agents. Acknowledging the common tone of American and Russian diplomatic relations, I find logical to define Putin’s move as a response to the American allegations that took place in 2017. Hence, I believe that the current list is a manifestation of dissatisfaction within a certain context and therefore, I find it unlikely that the list will further be used. Moreover, I find most likely that the 9 figure represents the number of medias deemed to generally interfere in Russian politics and will therefore remain as such. Hence, I assign a probability of 80% for the list to remain with 9 medias and 0% to be reduced. However, considering the latest claims of the French president Emmanuel Macron on Russian media, it is important to keep in mind that there is still a good possibility that Putin decides to enlarge the list in response to French politics, therefore assigning a probability of 20% to additional media to be designated by the Russian Ministry of Justice. Nevertheless, it is very unlikely that the number of potential medias to be added before June surpasses the number of medias that were designated after the events of 2017, therefore considering "more than 20" impossible.

The law was seemingly passed in direct response to increasing pressure in the US to have Russian US-based media outlets register as foreign agents. No media outlets have been added to the Russian list since 2017. Hence, the law seems to have been a ‘one-of’ response to the developments in the US. Hence, it seems very unlikely that the number of medias designated as foreign agents will surpass the current 9. Hence, the 8-10 interval is assigned a 95% probability. However, the pending results of the Mueller investigation in the US could increase tensions around any Russian media outlets in the US, and hence, Russia could retaliate by increasing the number of US entities on the list of foreign agents. This development (in the form of the 11-20 interval) is ascribed a 5 % probability.

https://www.nytimes.com/2017/11/15/world/europe/russia-news-media-foreign-agents.html the measure is claimed to habe been taken unwillingly to respond to US policy on Russian media. This extraordinary measure is not likely to be much more than a symbolic one meant to give US a message. The most likely outcome is for the 9 actual media outlets to remain the only ones on the list, even though there is a possibility for additional ones added.

At present, there are 9 media outlets on the Russian Ministry of Justice’s list of media designated as foreign agents since December 2017. Nevertheless, compared to the current context, it would not be surprising to see the list grow.

Since the law was passed, no other media outlets have been added to the list — it remains at 9. The law can be viewed as a direct reaction to the US move on RT America, a move to assert dominance and a warning to other media outlets. Both the underlying reasons for the implementation of the bill, and its overall effect on existing media outlets, give reason to believe that no other media outlets will be identified as foreign agents before June. Thus, it is expected that come June 1 the number will stand at 9.

As I see it this bill was signed (december 2017) for two reasons: 1) to ban a certain group of media outlets, and 2) to serve as a warning for big foreign media outlets. Since thhe bill was signed no other media outlets have been removed or added, and I see little signs in Russian media that others will follow soon.
Putin might get mad at someone, but he might also reward a media outlet as a favor to Trump.

Given that no additions have been made since the law was passed, it seems unlikely that Russia will add more agents to the list than the 9 it currently has. The law was perhaps mostly introduced to make a point and secondly to be able to act on unwanted media. It seems very unlikely that any of the outlets would come off the list, as I believe this might only be the case if they were forced to or decided to stop their activities in Russia. It may be a little more like that all the RFE/RL outlets close at the same time, taking the number below 3, rather than just one agent closing down. For Russia to add more agents to the list, something would need to happen to upset them, so e.g. US or another country would need to restrict Russia media or otherwise upset Putin, which seems seems most likely, if the US shows undoubtable evidence of Russia medling, but even then the US would probably, one would hope, try to think before acting and look for better ways to address this than open aggression through one sided measures.
Current count is 9, comrade

It's quite likely that Russia's disinformation campaign will spark continued journalistic "dissent." I can't envision the Kremlin's repression of news outlets running contrary to Russian propaganda as decelerating or simply remaining constant. I expect more "near abroad", that is, former USSR or Warsaw Pact, news outlets to be singled out.

I don't see any media getting removed from the list, reasons: 1) Russia/USA relationship is still strained, and the list appears to be a tit-for-tat instrument for Russia should the US crack down on Russian media in the US. 2) The more "domestic" media outlets on the list are on there for some reason determined by the Russian government, but I don't see the media outlets would change their stance after being put on the list. Also, if they went out of business, I doubt they would be removed from the list in that case. I see a low likelihood of media outlets being added. Possible scenarios: 1) tit-for-tat connected to some events in the US or elsewhere 2) more "domestic" media outlets will be deemed fit for the list For both scenarios, I also see about a 50:50 probability that only one media outlet gets added in one go. Given there are currently 9 on the list I guess overall I am estimating 30% probability that media outlets get added, 15% that multiple get added in one go. Should one single outlet get added to the list, will have to revise 11 to 20 bucket probability up.
